    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm studying for my structural mechanics exam. can u explain why we actually need to add steel rebar to concrete foundations? like why isnt the concrete itself enough to handle the loads? im a bit confused about the relationship between compressive and tensile strength here.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I can help with that. Concrete is excellent at handling compressive forces, but it isn't as strong when it comes to tension. Steel rebar, or reinforcing bars, are added to concrete to help it handle tensile stresses. When a concrete foundation is subjected to loads, the concrete can crush under compression, but it can crack and fail under tension. The steel rebar, being much stronger in tension, helps to hold the concrete together and distribute the loads more evenly, preventing the foundation from failing. Think of it as a team effort: concrete is great at pushing and holding things down, but steel rebar is the strong, reliable friend that helps when things start pulling apart.",
