    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, I can explain that. When tensile forces start to build up in the concrete, it begins to crack. These cracks are small at first, but as the forces continue to increase, the cracks can grow larger and more numerous. Eventually, the internal structure of the concrete can no longer hold, and the cracks can become so large that the concrete can no longer support the load. This is when the foundation starts to fail. It's like a bridge made of concrete: it can handle a lot of weight pushing down on it, but if a big enough force pulls from the sides, the bridge can start to break apart. The steel rebar helps to prevent this by taking on the tensile forces and holding the concrete together, like a strong, supportive hand.",
